  {title:'Webflow Pricing Overhaul Effective May 13 — Review Every Client Plan This Week',tier:'s',tierLabel:'S Tier',pipeline:'Webflow Build → Client Handoff',source:'Webflow Help Center',url:'https://help.webflow.com/hc/en-us/articles/51059955082387-Updated-pricing-and-simplified-plans-for-May-2026',benefit:'Webflow merged CMS and Business plans on May 13 — audit every client\'s plan this week and communicate changes before they see surprise billing.',roi:'Immediate',fit:5,why:'From May 13 Webflow replaced the CMS ($23/mo) and Business ($39/mo) plans with a single Premium Site plan ($25/mo annual / $39 monthly). CMS item limit doubled to 20,000, removing the $10/mo add-on for most sites. AI credits now included in all Workspace plans, with enforcement starting June 29. Existing clients keep current pricing until next renewal but need to know what\'s changing.',steps:['Map every client site to the new plan structure using the Webflow pricing calculator — identify who saves and who pays more.','Draft a short client email this week explaining the changes — proactive communication prevents angry billing surprises.','Update agency pricing proposals for new projects to use the new plan names and limits.'],impl:{Research:'1h',Build:'—',QA:'—',Rollout:'2h',Total:'3h'},impact:{'Build Speed':{val:'—',neutral:true},'QA Pass Rate':{val:'—',neutral:true},'Page Perf':{val:'—',neutral:true}},compat:{Webflow:'Yes',Figma:'No',n8n:'No',Cloudflare:'No',Playwright:'No','Website QA':'No'}},
  {title:'Google I/O 2026 — WebMCP, Prompt API, and Modern Web Guidance (May 19-20)',tier:'s',tierLabel:'S Tier',pipeline:'10-Template → Client Handoff',source:'Chrome for Developers',url:'https://developer.chrome.com/blog/chrome-at-io26',benefit:'Google I/O this week has 15 Chrome announcements — WebMCP, on-device AI, and 100+ expert web coding patterns are the three that change how we build.',roi:'High',fit:4,why:'Google I/O 2026 (May 19-20) confirmed Prompt API as stable (Gemini Nano, on-device, no API cost), launched WebMCP origin trial in Chrome 149 (structured tool interface for AI agents on websites), and published Modern Web Guidance — expert-vetted coding patterns for AI coding tools to use for performance, accessibility, and security. This is the clearest signal yet that AI-interactive websites are a near-term deliverable.',steps:['Watch the Chrome at I/O 2026 recording as a team — budget 45 min to identify features that affect current projects.','Prototype the Prompt API on one client page this sprint — a FAQ chatbot or text summariser takes about 2h.','Register interest in the WebMCP origin trial — access opens in Chrome 149.'],impl:{Research:'2h',Build:'4h',QA:'1h',Rollout:'1h',Total:'8h'},impact:{'Build Speed':{val:'+10%'},'QA Pass Rate':{val:'+5%'},'Page Perf':{val:'+10%'}},compat:{Webflow:'Partial',Figma:'No',n8n:'No',Cloudflare:'Yes',Playwright:'No','Website QA':'No'}},
  {title:'Google May 2026 Core Update Begins May 21 — Set Up Monitoring Before It Hits',tier:'s',tierLabel:'S Tier',pipeline:'SEO → Content Strategy',source:'Search Engine Journal',url:'https://www.searchenginejournal.com/google-begins-rolling-out-may-2026-core-update/575589/',benefit:'Google\'s second core update of 2026 starts this week — get rank tracking and CWV baselines in place before rankings shift.',roi:'Immediate',fit:5,why:'The May 2026 Core Update begins rolling out May 21. Practitioners expect it to be larger than the March update, which introduced holistic CWV scoring where failing one metric compounds the others. The first week of a core update is when the most monitoring value is captured — before vs after comparisons are only meaningful if you have a clean pre-update baseline.',steps:['Set up Google Search Console performance alerts for all client sites today — you want instant notification if impressions or clicks drop.','Run PageSpeed Insights on the top 5 pages per client right now and save the LCP/CLS/INP scores as a dated baseline.','Identify the 3 clients with the highest traffic and weakest CWV scores — these are highest risk and should be first in queue for optimisation.'],impl:{Research:'0.5h',Build:'—',QA:'2h',Rollout:'—',Total:'2.5h / site'},impact:{'Build Speed':{val:'—',neutral:true},'QA Pass Rate':{val:'—',neutral:true},'Page Perf':{val:'+20%'}},compat:{Webflow:'Yes',Figma:'No',n8n:'No',Cloudflare:'Yes',Playwright:'No','Website QA':'Yes'}},
  {title:'Playwright 1.60.0 JS Released — Native Drag-Drop, HAR Tracing, Better CI Errors',tier:'a',tierLabel:'A Tier',pipeline:'QA → Website QA',source:'Playwright Docs',url:'https://playwright.dev/docs/release-notes',benefit:'Playwright 1.60 ships `locator.drop()` for true drag-and-drop testing and `errorContext` ARIA snapshots that make CI failure logs actually readable.',roi:'High',fit:5,why:'Playwright 1.60.0 (May 11) adds `locator.drop()` — synthetic drag-and-drop with real DataTransfer objects, no more fragile mouse-event chains. `tracing.startHar()` makes HAR recording a first-class tracing API. `errorContext` surfaces an ARIA snapshot of the failing element in every assertion error — the single biggest debugging time-saver in a Playwright release this year.',steps:['Upgrade Playwright: `npm install @playwright/test@latest` — check reporter compatibility if using Currents (requires v2 upgrade).','Replace any drag-and-drop test workarounds with `locator.drop()` — more reliable and cross-browser.','Review the most recent CI failures with the new `errorContext` output — the ARIA snapshot makes root cause obvious at a glance.'],impl:{Research:'0.5h',Build:'1h',QA:'1h',Rollout:'0.5h',Total:'3h'},impact:{'Build Speed':{val:'+5%'},'QA Pass Rate':{val:'+25%'},'Page Perf':{val:'—',neutral:true}},compat:{Webflow:'Yes',Figma:'No',n8n:'No',Cloudflare:'No',Playwright:'Yes','Website QA':'Yes'}},
  {title:'CSS Field-Sizing Property — Auto-Growing Textareas Without JavaScript',tier:'a',tierLabel:'A Tier',pipeline:'Webflow Build → QA',source:'web.dev',url:'https://web.dev/blog/web-platform-05-2026',benefit:'`field-sizing: content` makes textareas auto-grow to fit content in pure CSS — remove every JavaScript auto-resize listener from client contact forms.',roi:'High',fit:4,why:'`field-sizing: content` is in Chrome stable and now in Firefox 152 beta, moving toward cross-browser Baseline. It makes `<textarea>` and `<input>` elements automatically grow and shrink based on content without any JavaScript. This removes one of the most commonly JS-handled UI patterns in Webflow custom code.',steps:['Add `field-sizing: content` to all textarea elements in the shared Webflow component library — wrap in `@supports (field-sizing: content)` during the Firefox beta period.','Remove existing JavaScript auto-resize event listeners — they conflict with the native behaviour.','Test edge cases: `max-height` + `overflow-y: auto` constrains growth correctly alongside `field-sizing: content`.'],impl:{Research:'0.5h',Build:'1h',QA:'1h',Rollout:'0.5h',Total:'3h'},impact:{'Build Speed':{val:'+10%'},'QA Pass Rate':{val:'+8%'},'Page Perf':{val:'+5%'}},compat:{Webflow:'Partial',Figma:'No',n8n:'No',Cloudflare:'No',Playwright:'Yes','Website QA':'Yes'}},
  {title:'Webflow AEO Announced — New Service Line Opportunity',tier:'a',tierLabel:'A Tier',pipeline:'SEO → Content Strategy',source:'Webflow Blog',url:'https://webflow.com/feature/aeo',benefit:'Webflow announced AEO at Google I/O — a built-in tool to measure and improve how clients appear in ChatGPT, Perplexity, and Gemini answers.',roi:'High',fit:4,why:'Announced at Google I/O (May 19) as part of the Webflow-Google partnership, Webflow AEO adds AI search analytics and AI-assisted recommendations for schema markup, alt text, and structured content. It requires a Team or Enterprise Workspace plan with the AI toggle on. The product fills a gap that clients are already asking about.',steps:['Enable Webflow AEO on the agency\'s own site and generate a baseline AI search visibility report this week.','Identify which client sites are on Team or Enterprise plans — they can access AEO now.','Build an AEO service pitch: client\'s current AI search visibility score and what a 3-month sprint would improve.'],impl:{Research:'1h',Build:'1h',QA:'1h',Rollout:'2h',Total:'5h'},impact:{'Build Speed':{val:'—',neutral:true},'QA Pass Rate':{val:'—',neutral:true},'Page Perf':{val:'+10%'}},compat:{Webflow:'Yes',Figma:'No',n8n:'Yes',Cloudflare:'No',Playwright:'No','Website QA':'Yes'}},
  {title:'Next.js 13 + 14 — No Security Patches, Upgrade Is the Only Fix',tier:'b',tierLabel:'B Tier',pipeline:'Webflow Build (Headless Only)',source:'Vercel Changelog',url:'https://vercel.com/changelog/next-js-may-2026-security-release',benefit:'Next.js 13 and 14 received no patches for the May CVEs — any client site still on these versions is exposed and needs a Next.js 15 upgrade scoped now.',roi:'Immediate',fit:3,why:'The May 7 Next.js security release patched 13 CVEs in versions 15.5.18 and 16.2.6 only. Next.js 13 and 14 received nothing and have no WAF-only mitigation for the SSRF and auth bypass vulnerabilities. Cloudflare shipped emergency WAF rules on May 7 as temporary cover for the segment-prefetch bypass, but it does not address all 13 CVEs.',steps:['Audit all headless Next.js client projects — note the Next.js version for each and flag anything on 13.x or 14.x.','Scope a Next.js 15 upgrade for each flagged project — the migration guide covers all breaking changes.','As interim mitigation, put any unpatched deployment behind Cloudflare with WAF rules enabled while scheduling the upgrade.'],impl:{Research:'1h',Build:'4h',QA:'3h',Rollout:'1h',Total:'9h / project'},impact:{'Build Speed':{val:'—',neutral:true},'QA Pass Rate':{val:'+10%'},'Page Perf':{val:'+5%'}},compat:{Webflow:'No',Figma:'No',n8n:'Partial',Cloudflare:'Yes',Playwright:'Yes','Website QA':'No'}},
  {title:'Webflow Changelog Attribution Preview — AI vs Human Edit Tracking Coming',tier:'c',tierLabel:'C Tier',pipeline:'Webflow Build → Client Handoff',source:'Webflow Updates',url:'https://webflow.com/updates',benefit:'Webflow is previewing changelog attribution that logs whether changes were made by a human, Webflow AI, or an MCP tool — useful context for compliance-sensitive client handoffs.',roi:'Watch',fit:3,why:'A preview of Webflow\'s changelog attribution feature is visible this week ahead of full release. When GA, every change will be attributed to its source: human, Webflow AI, or MCP tool. For agencies managing AI-assisted client builds, this provides the audit trail that documentation-conscious clients expect.',steps:['No immediate action required — monitor Webflow changelog for the GA announcement.','Plan to add "review AI changelog entries" to the QA checklist once the feature is fully available.','Identify which clients are most likely to ask about AI edit transparency — prepare a brief explanation of how the attribution trail works.'],impl:{Research:'0.5h',Build:'—',QA:'—',Rollout:'—',Total:'0.5h'},impact:{'Build Speed':{val:'—',neutral:true},'QA Pass Rate':{val:'+5%'},'Page Perf':{val:'—',neutral:true}},compat:{Webflow:'Yes',Figma:'No',n8n:'No',Cloudflare:'No',Playwright:'No','Website QA':'Yes'}}
