  {title:'Webflow Pricing Restructure — CMS + Business Plans Merge on May 13',tier:'s',tierLabel:'S Tier',pipeline:'Webflow Build → Client Handoff',source:'Webflow Help Center',url:'https://help.webflow.com/hc/en-us/articles/51059955082387-Updated-pricing-and-simplified-plans-for-May-2026',benefit:'Webflow is merging its CMS and Business plans into one on May 13 — review client billing now and communicate the changes before they appear on invoices.',roi:'Immediate',fit:5,why:'Starting May 13, Webflow replaces the CMS ($23/mo) and Business ($39/mo) site plans with a Premium Site plan at $25/mo annual / $39 monthly. The CMS item cap doubles from 10,000 to 20,000, removing the $10/mo CMS add-on for most sites. AI credits will be included in all Workspace plans. Clients on existing plans are not changed until next renewal but they need to hear this from you first.',steps:['Map every client site plan to the new structure using the Webflow pricing calculator — identify who gets better value and who may pay more.','Draft a client communication email this week explaining the May 13 changes — send before clients notice the change themselves.','Update pricing proposals for new client projects to use the new plan names and limits immediately.'],impl:{Research:'1h',Build:'—',QA:'—',Rollout:'2h',Total:'3h'},impact:{'Build Speed':{val:'—',neutral:true},'QA Pass Rate':{val:'—',neutral:true},'Page Perf':{val:'—',neutral:true}},compat:{Webflow:'Yes',Figma:'No',n8n:'No',Cloudflare:'No',Playwright:'No','Website QA':'No'}},
  {title:'Next.js Emergency Security Release — 13 CVEs Including Auth Bypass + SSRF (May 7)',tier:'s',tierLabel:'S Tier',pipeline:'Webflow Build (Headless Only)',source:'Vercel Changelog',url:'https://vercel.com/changelog/next-js-may-2026-security-release',benefit:'Upgrade all Next.js client deployments to 15.5.18 or 16.2.6 immediately — several CVEs allow attackers to bypass authentication and access internal infrastructure.',roi:'Immediate',fit:4,why:'Vercel patched 13 Next.js vulnerabilities on May 7. The most critical: SSRF via WebSocket upgrade headers that can expose cloud metadata endpoints, App Router auth bypass via crafted prefetch URLs, and cache poisoning in RSC responses. No patches exist for Next.js 13.x or 14.x — upgrading is the only mitigation. Cloudflare shipped emergency WAF rules as a temporary shield for unpatched deployments.',steps:['List all headless Next.js client deployments and their current version — this is priority zero this sprint.','Upgrade to Next.js 15.5.18 (or 16.2.6 if already on 16.x) — the migration guide covers breaking changes.','If immediate upgrade is not possible, enable Cloudflare WAF on all unpatched deployments as interim protection while you schedule the work.'],impl:{Research:'1h',Build:'3h',QA:'2h',Rollout:'1h',Total:'7h / project'},impact:{'Build Speed':{val:'—',neutral:true},'QA Pass Rate':{val:'+10%'},'Page Perf':{val:'—',neutral:true}},compat:{Webflow:'No',Figma:'No',n8n:'Partial',Cloudflare:'Yes',Playwright:'Yes','Website QA':'No'}},
  {title:'Chrome 148 Stable — Prompt API, Lazy Video/Audio Loading, Container Query Update (May 5)',tier:'a',tierLabel:'A Tier',pipeline:'Webflow Build → QA',source:'Chrome for Developers',url:'https://developer.chrome.com/blog/new-in-chrome-148',benefit:'Three immediate wins in Chrome 148: on-device AI with no backend costs, lazy loading for video and audio, and cleaner container query syntax.',roi:'High',fit:4,why:'Chrome 148 (stable May 5) ships the Prompt API (on-device Gemini Nano — AI features without API keys), `loading="lazy"` support for `<video>` and `<audio>` elements (free LCP improvement on media-heavy pages), and name-only container queries (simpler `@container name` syntax without specifying `container-type`). All three are usable in production today.',steps:['Add `loading="lazy"` to all non-above-the-fold `<video>` and `<audio>` elements across active client sites — one attribute, measurable LCP gain.','Test name-only container queries in Webflow custom code blocks — simpler syntax reduces specificity issues.','Prototype the Prompt API as a FAQ chatbot or page summariser on one client site — 2h build, zero backend cost.'],impl:{Research:'1h',Build:'2h',QA:'1h',Rollout:'1h',Total:'5h'},impact:{'Build Speed':{val:'+10%'},'QA Pass Rate':{val:'+5%'},'Page Perf':{val:'+15%'}},compat:{Webflow:'Partial',Figma:'No',n8n:'No',Cloudflare:'Yes',Playwright:'Yes','Website QA':'Yes'}},
  {title:'Playwright 1.60.0 Released — `locator.drop()`, HAR Tracing, ARIA Error Context',tier:'a',tierLabel:'A Tier',pipeline:'QA → Website QA',source:'Playwright Docs',url:'https://playwright.dev/docs/release-notes',benefit:'Playwright 1.60 brings true drag-and-drop testing and CI failure logs that are actually useful — upgrade now before the next QA sprint.',roi:'High',fit:5,why:'Playwright 1.60.0 (May 11) adds `locator.drop()` for synthetic drag-and-drop with real DataTransfer objects, `tracing.startHar()` for first-class HAR network recording, and `errorContext` that shows an ARIA snapshot of the failing element in every assertion error. The last feature alone is the most impactful debugging improvement in a Playwright release this year.',steps:['Upgrade Playwright: `npm install @playwright/test@latest` — if using Currents as your reporter, upgrade to their v2 before running.','Replace any existing drag-and-drop test workarounds with `locator.drop()` — more reliable and cross-browser.','Run your last failed CI job with 1.60 and read the `errorContext` ARIA snapshot — it makes root cause obvious.'],impl:{Research:'0.5h',Build:'1h',QA:'1h',Rollout:'0.5h',Total:'3h'},impact:{'Build Speed':{val:'+5%'},'QA Pass Rate':{val:'+25%'},'Page Perf':{val:'—',neutral:true}},compat:{Webflow:'Yes',Figma:'No',n8n:'No',Cloudflare:'No',Playwright:'Yes','Website QA':'Yes'}},
  {title:'CSS Container Style Queries — Cross-Browser Baseline (Firefox 151)',tier:'a',tierLabel:'A Tier',pipeline:'Webflow Build → QA',source:'web.dev',url:'https://web.dev/blog/web-platform-05-2026',benefit:'Container style queries on custom properties are now cross-browser — remove `@supports` wrappers and replace JS class toggling with pure CSS.',roi:'High',fit:4,why:'Firefox 151 shipped container style queries (`@container style()`), completing cross-browser support. This lets components change appearance based on the value of a CSS custom property on their container — enabling theme switching, state-based styling, and component variants entirely in CSS without JavaScript class toggling.',steps:['Audit Webflow custom code for any JavaScript that toggles classes purely for visual state — replace with container style queries.','Remove `@supports (container-type: inline-size)` wrappers from existing container query code — all major browsers support it now.','Add a container style query pattern to the shared CSS library for theme and variant switching.'],impl:{Research:'0.5h',Build:'2h',QA:'1h',Rollout:'0.5h',Total:'4h'},impact:{'Build Speed':{val:'+15%'},'QA Pass Rate':{val:'+10%'},'Page Perf':{val:'+5%'}},compat:{Webflow:'Partial',Figma:'No',n8n:'No',Cloudflare:'No',Playwright:'Yes','Website QA':'Yes'}},
  {title:'Google Maps Heatmap Layer + Drawing Library Removed (May 2026)',tier:'a',tierLabel:'A Tier',pipeline:'Webflow Build → Client Handoff',source:'Google Maps Platform',url:'https://developers.google.com/maps/deprecations',benefit:'Two deprecated Google Maps API features are now permanently unavailable — client sites using them have broken map functionality and need an urgent fix.',roi:'Immediate',fit:3,why:'`google.maps.visualization.HeatmapLayer` (deprecated May 2025) and the Drawing Library `google.maps.drawing.*` (deprecated August 2025) both went permanently unavailable this month. They now throw errors with no graceful fallback. The Maps API has no direct replacement for either — deck.gl is Google\'s recommended heatmap alternative.',steps:['Search all client codebases and Webflow embeds for `HeatmapLayer`, `google.maps.visualization`, and `google.maps.drawing` — any match is broken right now.','Replace Heatmap Layer with deck.gl\'s HeatmapLayer or a static heatmap image depending on client needs.','Add Google Maps deprecation checks to the annual client site review process.'],impl:{Research:'1h',Build:'3h',QA:'1h',Rollout:'1h',Total:'6h'},impact:{'Build Speed':{val:'—',neutral:true},'QA Pass Rate':{val:'+10%'},'Page Perf':{val:'—',neutral:true}},compat:{Webflow:'Partial',Figma:'No',n8n:'No',Cloudflare:'No',Playwright:'Yes','Website QA':'Yes'}},
  {title:'CSS `:open` Pseudo-Class — Cross-Browser Baseline (Safari 26.5)',tier:'b',tierLabel:'B Tier',pipeline:'Webflow Build → QA',source:'web.dev',url:'https://web.dev/blog/web-platform-05-2026',benefit:'Style open dropdowns, dialogs, and date pickers in pure CSS without JavaScript — `:open` is now supported across all major browsers.',roi:'Medium',fit:4,why:'Safari 26.5 completed cross-browser support for the `:open` pseudo-class, which lets you style `<details>`, `<dialog>`, `<select>`, and input pickers when in the open state. Previously this required JavaScript class toggling on open/close events — a common source of accessibility bugs.',steps:['Add `:open` state styles to all `<details>` disclosure components in the shared library — remove JS toggle listeners.','Style `<dialog>` backdrop and content using `:open` for modal components in headless projects.','Remove any `data-open` attribute workarounds used to style open states — the native pseudo-class replaces them.'],impl:{Research:'0.5h',Build:'2h',QA:'1h',Rollout:'0.5h',Total:'4h'},impact:{'Build Speed':{val:'+10%'},'QA Pass Rate':{val:'+8%'},'Page Perf':{val:'+5%'}},compat:{Webflow:'Partial',Figma:'No',n8n:'No',Cloudflare:'No',Playwright:'Yes','Website QA':'Yes'}},
  {title:'Webflow List Assets API — Folder Filtering Now Available (May 5)',tier:'c',tierLabel:'C Tier',pipeline:'Webflow Build → Client Handoff',source:'Webflow Developer Changelog',url:'https://developers.webflow.com/home/changelog/2026/5/5',benefit:'The Webflow List Assets endpoint now filters by folder — removes the need to paginate all assets and filter in your own code.',roi:'Watch',fit:3,why:'The List Assets endpoint previously returned all site assets regardless of folder. From May 5 it accepts a folder parameter and returns per-asset folder context in the response. For n8n workflows or custom scripts managing Webflow media libraries, this reduces payload size and simplifies the automation logic.',steps:['Update any n8n Webflow API nodes that paginate all assets — add the folder parameter to scope the request.','Update type definitions in any TypeScript integrations using the Assets endpoint.','No urgent action if you do not currently use the Assets API.'],impl:{Research:'0.5h',Build:'1h',QA:'0.5h',Rollout:'0.5h',Total:'2.5h'},impact:{'Build Speed':{val:'+5%'},'QA Pass Rate':{val:'+5%'},'Page Perf':{val:'—',neutral:true}},compat:{Webflow:'Yes',Figma:'No',n8n:'Yes',Cloudflare:'No',Playwright:'No','Website QA':'No'}}
